AFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:tomato;\"|'''OUT'''\n|rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"25\" style=\"background:darkgrey\"| \n|-\n|Sarah S.\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:tomato;\"|'''OUT'''\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|19-20\n|{{nowrap|Cassandra}}\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:orange;\"|'''LOW'''\n|style=\"background:darkred;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''OUT'''</span>\n|rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"25\" style=\"background:darkgrey\"| \n|-\n|Marie\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:orange;\"|'''LOW'''\n|style=\"background:darkred;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''OUT'''</span>\n|-\n!rowspan=\"3\"|21-23\n|Alina\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:tomato;\"|'''OUT'''\n|rowspan=\"3\" colspan=\"25\" style=\"background:darkgrey\"| \n|-\n|Laura\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:tomato;\"|'''OUT'''\n|-\n|Valeria\n|style=\"background:darkgrey;\"|\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:tomato;\"|'''OUT'''\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|24-25\n|Malin\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:tomato;\"|'''OUT'''\n|rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"25\" style=\"background:darkgrey\"| \n|-\n|Saskia\n|SAFE\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:tomato;\"|'''OUT'''\n|-\n!rowspan=\"3\"|26-28 \n|Charlotte\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:tomato;\"|'''OUT'''\n|rowspan=\"3\" colspan=\"25\" style=\"background:darkgrey\"| \n|-\n|Daria\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:tomato;\"|'''OUT'''\n|-\n|{{nowrap|Nina-Sue}}\n|SAFE\n|style=\"background:tomato;\"|'''OUT'''\n|}\n\n:{{Color box|tomato|border=darkgray}} The contestant was eliminated\n:{{Color box|darkred|border=darkgray}} The contestant was eliminated outside of judging panel\n:{{Color box|orange|border=darkgray}} The contestant was in danger of elimination\n:{{Color box|limegreen|border=darkgray}} The contestant won the competition\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Photo shoot guide===\n*'''Episode 2 photo shoot:''' Posing in the jungle in groups with a male model\n*'''Episode 3 photo shoot:''' Nude on the beach with a horse\n*'''Episode 4 photo shoot:''' Jumping while posing as action stars\n*'''Episode 5 photo shoot:''' Sedcard\n*'''Episode 6 photo shoot:''' Beauty shoot with tarantulas, scorpions or cockroaches\n*'''Episode 7 photo shoot:''' Portraying [[Marilyn Monroe]] in a box on the [[Walk of Fame]]\n*'''Episode 8 photo shoot:''' Posing at the end of the runway in ''Christian Cowan'' gowns\n*'''Episode 9 photo shoot:''' Posing in groups while being splashed with colored powder in a desert\n*'''Episode 10 video shoot:''' Portraying cowgirls while acting out a fighting scene\n*'''Episode 11 photo shoot:''' Portraying Underwater princesses while posing with a  male model\n*'''Episode 12 photo shoot:'''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.prosieben.de/tv/germanys-next-topmodel ''Official Website'']\n\n{{Germany's Next Topmodel}}\n\n[[Category:2020 German television seasons]]\n[[Category:Germany's Next Topmodel]]\n", "name_user": "93.192.120.247", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSummaries:Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germany%27s_Next_Topmodel_(season_15)"}
{"title_page": "Beavis and Butt-Head Do America", "text_new": "{{short description|1996 American animated road comedy film directed by Mike Judge}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Beavis and Butt-Head Do America\n| image = Beavis And Butthead Do America.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Mike Judge]]\n| producer = Abby Terkuhle\n| writers = {{Plainlist|\n* Mike Judge\n* [[Joe Stillman]]\n}}\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[Beavis and Butt-Head]]''|Mike Judge}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* Mike Judge\n* [[Demi Moore]]\n* [[Bruce Willis]]\n* [[Robert Stack]]\n* [[Cloris Leachman]]\n}}\n| music = [[John Frizzell (composer)|John Frizzell]]\n| editing = {{Plainlist|\n* Gunter Glinka\n* Terry Kelley\n* Neil Lawrence\n}}\n| color_process = [[Deluxe Entertainment Services Group|Deluxe]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[MTV Films|MTV]]<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Film/59989-BEAVIS-ANDBUTT-HEADDOAMERICA?sid=5593bdb3-7795-42b1-9261-5e4aee61c9de&sr=0.7080989&cp=1&pos=0|title=Beavis and Butt-Head Do America|work=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Geffen Pictures]]<ref name=afi/>\n}}\n| distributor = [[Paramount Pictures]]<ref name=afi/>\n| released = {{Film date|1996|12|20}}\n| runtime = 81 minutes<!-- US theatrical runtime: 80:57 --><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/AFF066576/ |title=Title << British Board of Film Classification |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=January 13, 1997 |accessdate=July 8, 2011}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $12 million<ref name=\"Budget\"/>\n| gross = $63.1 million (US)<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | title=Beavis and Butt-Head Do America (1996 film) | publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=beavisandbuttheaddoamerica.htm | accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America''''' is a 1996 American [[comedy film]]<!-- Please seek consensus at the talk page before changing/adding genres --> based on the [[MTV]] animated television series ''[[Beavis and Butt-Head]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title= Road Trip the Right Vehicle for Beavis and Butt-head|work= The Los Angeles Times|date=December 20, 1996|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1996-12-20/entertainment/ca-10832_1_mike-judge|accessdate=November 8, 2010|first=Kevin|last=Thomas}}</ref> Co-written and directed by series creator [[Mike Judge]], the film  stars the regular television cast of Judge with guest performances by [[Demi Moore]], [[Bruce Willis]], [[Robert Stack]] and [[Cloris Leachman]]. The film centers on [[Beavis]] and [[Butt-Head]] as they travel across the country in an attempt to [[Sexual intercourse|score]].\n\nPrevious offers by MTV to create a film version of ''Beavis and Butt-Head'' were rejected by Judge, but he eventually accepted one in 1994. When the film went into production, Judge and the show's staff halted production on the series while Judge and [[Joe Stillman]] wrote the script. They conceived numerous plot ideas with Judge's being the one developed into a film. [[John Frizzell (composer)|John Frizzell]] composed the film's score.\n\n''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America'' was praised by critics and proved to be a major box office hit from its release on December 20, 1996 by [[Paramount Pictures]], grossing $63.1 million in the United States, becoming the biggest December box office opening in history until it was beaten the following year by ''[[Scream 2]]'' and subsequently one week later by ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''. Although not the only time a feature film was based on an MTV cartoon, it was MTV's only theatrically released animated film.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Beavis]] and [[Butt-Head]] wake up from a dream(about destroying a city as giants) and discover that someone has stolen their [[television]], and they set out to find it. After several failed attempts to get a TV, they come across a motel which offers one in every room. They meet Muddy Grimes, who thinks that the boys are the [[Contract killing|hitmen]] he has contacted. Muddy offers Beavis and Butt-Head $10,000 to \"[[Murder|do]]\" his wife, Dallas. Thinking that \"do\" refers to sex, Butt-Head convinces Beavis that both of them can \"score\" and get paid enough to buy a new TV. Muddy hands them a photo of Dallas with instructions on where to find her and drives them to the airport to catch a plane to [[Las Vegas]].\n\nAfter arriving in the casino, Beavis and Butt-Head are ushered to the room Muddy booked, which is located next to Dallas's. They [[Eavesdropping|eavesdrop]] on the opposite room but are caught by Dallas. Dallas offers them $20,000 to go back and \"do\" Muddy, which they refuse. When Beavis (who has removed his pants) and Butt-Head begin arguing over who will \"do\" Dallas first, she realizes that they have misunderstood what they have been hired for. While they are fist fighting, she plants a stolen [[Biological agent|biological weapon]] known as the \"X-5 Unit\" in Beavis's pants in order to get rid of it. She then gets them tickets on a tour bus en route to [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C]]. and instructs them that she will be waiting for them in the [[US Capitol]] and will let them \"do her\" there.\n\nThe stolen bioweapon attracts the attention of the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms|ATF]], headed by Agent Flemming, who orders a [[body cavity search]] on everyone he encounters. Flemming becomes convinced that the duo are [[Criminal mastermind|criminal masterminds]] after they accidentally release the water behind the [[Hoover Dam]], cutting the power to Las Vegas. They are placed on the FBI's most wanted list. After a visit to the [[Grand Canyon]] and [[Yellowstone National Park]],  they fail return to the tour bus on time. Beavis and Butt-Head accidentally ride a busload of [[Nun|nuns]]; repulsed by the boys' actions, the nuns later abandon them at a gift shop in [[Petrified Forest National Park]]. They are then told Washington is about 2,000 miles away and begin to hike until they reach the [[desert]] where they meet two former [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] [[Road crew|roadies]] who are heavily implied to be their fathers, but part ways before they can make the connection.\n\nThe next day the boys begin to hike once more, but they soon collapse from [[dehydration]]. Beavis has a series of hallucinations(animated by [[Rob Zombie]]) after eating a [[Peyote|peyote cacti]] (thinking that there's water inside.) They are eventually found by Muddy, who plans to kill them after realizing they were not the hitmen he hired. However, after hearing that Dallas is going to meet up with the duo in Washington, Muddy decides to take them the rest of the way in his trunk to hunt her down. The boys escape by jumping onto the interstate, inadvertently causing a 400-car [[Multiple-vehicle collision|pileup]]. They casually walk past the scene and get back on the tour bus, stopping at the Capitol before finally reaching the [[White House]]. Before Dallas can meet with Beavis and Butt-Head to recover the bioweapon, she is confronted in the [[Multistorey car park|parking garage]] by Muddy. Dallas, however, seduces him and they briefly reconcile and have sex in his car. The ATF catches them on the act and faced with the possibility of a 60-year jail sentence. Dallas betrays Muddy by saying that he hid the bioweapon in Beavis's pants.\n\nThe ATF is dispatched to the White House due to Beavis and Butt-Head being there on the same day as a peace conference. Beavis consumes [[Caffeine|caffeine pills]], [[sugar]], and [[coffee]] while on the White House tour, transforming him into [[Cornholio]]. Cornholio wanders into the [[Oval Office]] and picks up the [[Moscow\u2013Washington hotline|red phone]], causing the military to go to [[DEFCON 4]]. Meanwhile, Butt-Head tries hitting on [[Chelsea Clinton]], but he gets thrown out of her bedroom window as well as detained and cavity searched by ATF officers. Beavis leaves the White House and goes to Mr. Anderson's [[Caravan (towed trailer)|trailer]], where Anderson catches him after catching him \"[[Masturbation|whacking off]]\" and throws him out. The ATF spots Beavis walking around the camper pants-less and confronts him, thinking he has the bioweapon on him. As the ATF is about to open fire, Anderson opens his camper door and throws out Beavis's pants. The pants are ripped open by the ATF, with the bioweapon flying out of them. The weapon lands safely in Butt-Head's hand, who then hands it to Flemming. Blame for the crime is ultimately pinned on Anderson and his wife, who are accused of trying to frame Beavis and Butt-Head, and arrested along with Dallas and Muddy. Flemming informs the boys that they are heroes and their adventure will remain [[Classified information|top secret]]. They meet President [[Bill Clinton]], who makes them honorary ATF agents. Beavis and Butt-Head return to Highland and find their TV in front of the motel.\n\n==Voice cast==\n{| style=\"float:right\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top\"\n|[[File:Demi Moore 2010 Time 100 Shankbone.jpg|thumb|upright|none|[[Demi Moore]] voices Dallas Grimes]]\n|[[File:Bruce Willis by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|none|[[Bruce Willis]] voices Muddy Grimes]]\n|[[File:Mike Judge by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|none|Mike Judge, voice of Beavis and Butt-head for TV, returned to work on the film]]\n|}\n<!-- main cast only -->\n* [[Mike Judge]] as [[Beavis]], [[Butt-Head]],  [[List of Beavis and Butt-Head characters#Tom Anderson|Tom Anderson (Old Guy with Camper)]],  [[List of Beavis and Butt-Head characters#Mr. Van Driessen|Van Driessen (Hippie Teacher)]], and [[List of Beavis and Butt-Head characters#Highland High faculty and staff|Principal McVicker]]\n* [[Bruce Willis]] as Muddy Grimes\n* [[Demi Moore]] as Dallas Grimes\n* [[Cloris Leachman]] as Old Woman On Plane and Bus\n* [[Robert Stack]] as Agent Flemming\n\n<!-- also starring voice cast in alpha order, closing credits -->\nOther voice actors include: Jacqueline Barba, [[Pamela Blair]], [[Eric Bogosian]], [[Kristofor Brown]], Tony Darling, [[John Doman]], Francis DuMaurier, [[Jim Flaherty]], Tim Guinee, Earl Hofert, [[Toby Huss]], [[Sam Johnson]], [[Richard Linklater]], Rosemary McNamara, Harsh Nayyar, [[Karen Phillips]], Dale Reeves, Mike Ruschak, and Gail Thomas\n\n[[Greg Kinnear]] had an uncredited role as ATF Agent Bork,<ref name=\"cinemablend\">https://www.cinemablend.com/dvds/Beavis-Butthead-Do-America-Special-Collector-Edition-1817.html</ref> [[David Letterman]] had a role as a [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] [[roadie]] and was credited under \"Earl Hofert\".<ref name=\"ifc\">https://www.ifc.com/2016/01/15-things-you-might-not-know-about-beavis-and-butt-head</ref>\n\n==Production==\nDevelopment for the film began in 1993 as part of a production deal with [[MTV]], [[David Geffen]], and [[Warner Bros.]] Geffen so believed in the potential of the ''Beavis and Butt-head'' TV series that he suggested creating a movie and record album based on the program. They originally conceived it as a live action movie, with ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' regulars [[David Spade]] and [[Adam Sandler]] in mind to play the title characters. After MTV's parent company [[Viacom (original)|Viacom]] purchased [[Paramount Pictures]] in 1994, the studio became a partner in the film, replacing Warner's interest in the project and dropping the live action concept under pressure from ''Beavis and Butt-Head'' creator [[Mike Judge]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Geffen Camp Heh-Hehs All the Way to the Bank |date=January 17, 1997 |work=The Los Angeles Times |first=Claudia |last=Ellen |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997-01-17/business/fi-19392_1_david-geffen}}</ref> Judge has stated production of the animated film was very [[ad hoc]] and had some difficulties with progressing due to most of the staff's television background. Beavis' hallucination sequence's design and animation was based on the works of [[Rob Zombie]]. The sequence's director was [[Chris Prynoski]]. <!-- This information is taken from the 2006 DVD release's end credits. -->\n\n===Deleted scene===\nWhen the film premiered on MTV on August 7, 1999, an additional [[deleted scene]] followed the airing: while visiting the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]], Beavis attempts to [[Defecation|use the restroom]], but cannot because of the lack of toilet paper in the stall. Coincidentally, Butt-head is angry because the urinals lack the automatic flushing mechanisms that had amazed him at [[Yellowstone National Park]]. After the rest of their tour group finishes looking at the encased [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]], Beavis sneaks out, breaks the glass with the U.S. flag pole, and steals it to use as \"T.P. for his bunghole.\" While Archive guards rush to see what happened, Beavis cleans up, and exits the stall with a piece of the Declaration, containing [[John Hancock]]'s signature, stuck to his shoe. The scene does not appear on the DVD, although it is mentioned on the disc's commentary track. In the track, Judge noted that the scene did not [[test screening|test]] well.{{Citation needed|date=June 2007}} Another alternate scene was done for when Butt-Head meets [[Chelsea Clinton]] in her bedroom, which showed her packing up to leave the White House. This alternate scene was created in the event [[Bill Clinton]] lost his [[1996 United States presidential election|1996 re-election bid]] to [[Bob Dole]]. However, by the spring of 1996, Judge ultimately decided to keep the original scene because he felt that it was looking as if Clinton was going to win his bid for re-election, and did so that November.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America'' opened in North America on December 20, 1996, and earned $63.1 million at the US box office after opening at #1 with $20.1 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=1996&wknd=51&p=.htm |title=Weekend Box Office Results for December 20-22, 1996 |publisher=Box Office Mojo |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> It had a $12 million production budget.<ref name=\"Budget\">{{cite news|title= Beavis and Butt-head Make Creator and Paramount Proud|work= The Los Angeles Times|date=December 24, 1996|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1996-12-24/entertainment/ca-12081_1_paramount-pictures|accessdate=November 8, 2010 |first=Elaine |last=Dutka}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe film held a 72% approval rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 53 reviews, with a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 6.18/10. The consensus is: \"''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America'' is unabashedly offensive, unapologetically stupid, and unexpectedly funny.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/beavis_and_butt_head_do_america | title=Beavis and Butt-head Do America | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] | accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a 64 out of 100 rating based on 16 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/beavis-and-butt-head-do-america | title=Beavis and Butt-head Do America | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' praised the film as a \"vulgar\" satire on American youth, and compared it favorably  to ''[[Wayne's World (film)|Wayne's World]]''.<ref>[http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/beavis-and-butt-head-do-america-1996 Roger Ebert's review of ''Beavis and Butt-head Do America]</ref> On the movie review show ''[[Siskel and Ebert]]'', Ebert's reviewing partner [[Gene Siskel]] gave the film a \"modest recommendation\", having been taken with the two lead characters. Ebert and Siskel ultimately awarded it a \"[[two thumbs up]]\" rating.<ref>[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=XciJEIa8KIE Siskel and Ebert review ''Beavis and Butt-head Do America'']</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Organization !! Award || Awardee || Result || Citation\n|-\n| [[BMI Awards|BMI Film & TV Awards]] || BMI Film Music Award || [[John Frizzell]] || {{won}} || {{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n|-\n| [[1997 MTV Movie Awards]] || Best On-Screen Duo || rowspan=3 | [[Beavis and Butt-Head]] || {{nom}} || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/archive/year.jhtml?year=1997|title=1997 MTV Movie Awards|work=[[MTV.com]]|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[17th Golden Raspberry Awards]] || Worst New Star || {{nom}} || rowspan=2|<ref>{{cite book|title=The Official Razzie Movie Guide|last=Wilson|first=John|publisher=[[Grand Central Publishing]]|year=2007|isbn=9780446510080|chapter=Seventeenth Annual Razzies (1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bLpJHjGFNk8C&pg=PT259}}</ref>\n|-\n| Worst Screen Couple || {{nom}}\n|}\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released on [[VHS]] on June 10, 1997 and on [[DVD]] on November 23, 1999, by [[Paramount Home Entertainment]]. The bonus features on the disc were a [[widescreen]] presentation, and two theatrical trailers. The film was re-released on a Special Edition DVD in 2006 as \"The Edition That Doesn't Suck\". It contained more in the way of bonus features such as [[Audio commentary|audio commentaries]], Spanish language tracks, more trailers, \"Making of\" documentaries, and more. It lacks the deleted National Archives scene. In 2013, \"The Edition That Doesn't Suck\" was re-released on DVD exclusively by Warner Home Video, under a deal with Paramount. Oddly enough, Warner Bros. was Geffen's distributor until The Geffen Company went bankrupt. Today, Warner Bros. holds home video distribution rights to all of Geffen Pictures' library.\n\n==Future==\n===Possible sequel===\nIn the years following, many fans rumored the possibility of a sequel or follow-up to the film, tentatively titled ''Beavis and Butt-Head: The Sequel''<ref name=\"screenrant.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/beavis-and-butt-head-movie-mike-judge-kofi-23670/|title=Beavis and Butt-Head: The Sequel?|last=Outlaw|first=Kofi|date=August 31, 2009|website=[[Screen Rant]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610183835/https://screenrant.com/beavis-and-butt-head-movie-mike-judge/|archive-date=June 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> or ''Beavis and Butt-Head 2''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://cinemablend.com/new/Comic-Con-Mike-Judge-Teases-Beavis-Butt-Head-2-14086.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-09-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004002256/http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Comic-Con-Mike-Judge-Teases-Beavis-Butt-Head-2-14086.html |archive-date=2016-10-04 |url-status=live }}</ref> On August 31, 2009, during the promotion of ''[[Extract (film)|Extract]]'', [[Mike Judge]] said he would like to see Beavis and Butt-Head on the big screen again.<ref name=\"screenrant.com\"/>\n\n===Possible live-action reboot===\nIn 2019 Judge, revealed that he has \"some ideas\" for a new film, saying there might be potential for a live-action version of the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/mike-judge-has-some-ideas-for-new-beavis-and-butt-head-movie|title=Mike Judge has \"some ideas\" for new Beavis and Butt-Head movie|last=Hammer|first=Alice Pattillo2019-07-29T12:08:36Z Metal|website=Metal Hammer Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Beavis and Butt-Head Do America: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = various artists\n| cover      = \n| caption    = \n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 5, 1996\n| recorded   = 1995\u201396\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]<br>[[alternative rock]]<br>[[punk rock]]<br>[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=49|s=00}}\n| label      = [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Mike Judge]] <small>([[Executive producer|exec.]])</small>|[[Butthole Surfers]]|[[Isaac Hayes]]|[[Silkski|Jerome Evans]]|[[John Frizzell (composer)|John Frizzell]]|[[Lars Frederiksen]]|Mark Williams|[[Moby]]|[[No Doubt]]|[[Rashad Smith]]|[[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]|[[Southern Culture on the Skids]]|[[Sylvia Massy]]|[[Terry Date]]|[[Tim Armstrong]]|[[Ulrich Wild]]|[[Vanda & Young]]|[[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie]]}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Beavis and Butt-Head Do America: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n | type        = soundtrack\n | single1     = [[Lesbian Seagull]]\n | single1date = 1996\n | single2     = [[Love Rollercoaster#Red Hot Chili Peppers version|Love Rollercoaster]]\n | single2date = November 1996\n | single3     = [[Ain't Nobody#LL Cool J version|Ain't Nobody]]\n | single3date = November 26, 1996\n | single4     = Walk On Water\n | single4date = 1996\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|2|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r241210|pure_url=yes}} link]\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2Score = C [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,294925_2,00.html link]\n}}\n# \"Two Cool Guys\" \u2013 [[Isaac Hayes]] (3:06)\n# \"[[Love Rollercoaster#Red Hot Chili Peppers cover version|Love Rollercoaster]]\" \u2013 [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] (4:37)\n# \"[[Ain't Nobody#LL Cool J version|Ain't Nobody]]\" \u2013 [[LL Cool J]] (4:38)\n# \"Ratfinks, Suicide Tanks and Cannibal Girls\" \u2013 [[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie]] (3:53)\n# \"I Wanna Riot\" \u2013 [[Rancid (band)|Rancid]] with [[Stubborn All-Stars]] (3:59)\n# \"Walk on Water\" \u2013 [[Ozzy Osbourne]] (4:18) *\n# \"Snakes\" \u2013 [[No Doubt]] (4:34)\n# \"Pimp'n Ain't EZ\" \u2013 Madd Head (4:21)\n# \"The Lord Is a Monkey\" (Rock Version) \u2013 [[Butthole Surfers]] (4:44)\n# \"White Trash\" \u2013 [[Southern Culture on the Skids]] (2:03)\n# \"[[Powerage|Gone Shootin']]\" \u2013 [[AC/DC]] (5:05)\n# \"[[Lesbian Seagull]]\" \u2013 [[Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)|Engelbert Humperdinck]] (3:39)\n\nNoticeably missing are \"Mucha Muchacha\", the version of \"[[Lesbian Seagull]]\" with Mr. Van Driessen singing, and the score tracks performed by The London Metropolitan Orchestra, which were released on a separate album.\n\n\"Two Cool Guys\", written and performed by [[Soul music|soul]]/[[funk]] musician Isaac Hayes, is a semi-parody of Hayes' [[Academy Award]]-winning \"[[Theme from Shaft|Theme from ''Shaft'']]\". It incorporates the theme from the ''Beavis and Butt-head'' television series as a rhythm guitar line, and series creator Mike Judge, who wrote the theme, is given a co-writing credit with Hayes in the soundtrack liner notes. The opening credit sequence which the song features in is a take-off on popular 1970s cop movies and TV shows with Beavis and Butt-Head as hip ace sleuth Lothario detectives.\n\nThe version of Ozzy Osbourne's \"Walk on Water\" is not the same version included in the film. The film used an earlier demo version, while the soundtrack itself contains a later, revised version. The original demo, which appears in the film, can be found on Osbourne's ''Prince of Darkness'' box set.  Ozzy and co-writer [[Jim Vallance]] both prefer the demo version heard in the film.<ref>{{cite web |title=Walk On Water |url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-osbourne-ozzy-walk.html |website=JimVallance.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414024542/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-osbourne-ozzy-walk.html |archive-date=2015-04-14}}</ref> \"Walk on Water\" was released as a single and peaked at number 28 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Billboard'' singles chart history-Ozzy Osbourne |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=ozzy osbourne|chart=all}} |accessdate=February 17, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090220005053/{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=ozzy osbourne|chart=all}}| archivedate= February 20, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0115641|Beavis and Butt-Head Do America}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.beavis-butthead.com:80/|title=Beavis and Butt-Head Do America official site}}\n* {{mojo title|beavisandbuttheaddoamerica|Beavis and Butt-Head Do America}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|beavis_and_butt_head_do_america|Beavis and Butt-Head Do America}}\n* ''[http://www.bcdb.com/bcdb/cartoon.cgi?film=23613&cartoon=Beavis%20and%20Butt-head%20Do%20America Beavis and Butt-head Do America]'' at the [[Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n* [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20199864,00.html ''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America'' Review] on ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n* [http://consequenceofsound.net/2009/07/cinema-sounds-beavis-butt-head-do-america-original-motion-picture-soundtrack/ ''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America'' review] on [[Consequence of Sound]]\n\n{{Beavis and Butt-Head}}\n{{Mike Judge}}\n{{MTV Films}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beavis And Butt-Head Do America}}\n[[Category:1996 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Beavis and Butt-Head]]\n[[Category:1996 animated films]]\n[[Category:1990s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s American animated films]]\n[[Category:1990s buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s road movies]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action comedy films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]]\n[[Category:American buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:American crime comedy films]]\n[[Category:American high school films]]\n[[Category:American political comedy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy road movies]]\n[[Category:Animated action films]]\n[[Category:Animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:Animated buddy films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated films based on animated series]]\n[[Category:Animated films about friendship]]\n[[Category:Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about drugs]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mike Judge]]\n[[Category:Films based on television series]]\n[[Category:Films set in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films set in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Films set in Texas]]\n[[Category:Films set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Films set in Wyoming]]\n[[Category:The Geffen Film Company films]]\n[[Category:MTV Films films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures animated films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Rough Draft Studios films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Joe Stillman]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Mike Judge]]\n[[Category:1996 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1996 American animated road comedy film directed by Mike Judge}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Beavis and Butt-Head Do America\n| image = Beavis And Butthead Do America.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Mike Judge]]\n| producer = Abby Terkuhle\n| writers = {{Plainlist|\n* Mike Judge\n* [[Joe Stillman]]\n}}\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[Beavis and Butt-Head]]''|Mike Judge}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* Mike Judge\n* [[Demi Moore]]\n* [[Bruce Willis]]\n* [[Robert Stack]]\n* [[Cloris Leachman]]\n}}\n| music = [[John Frizzell (composer)|John Frizzell]]\n| editing = {{Plainlist|\n* Gunter Glinka\n* Terry Kelley\n* Neil Lawrence\n}}\n| color_process = [[Deluxe Entertainment Services Group|Deluxe]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[MTV Films|MTV]]<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Film/59989-BEAVIS-ANDBUTT-HEADDOAMERICA?sid=5593bdb3-7795-42b1-9261-5e4aee61c9de&sr=0.7080989&cp=1&pos=0|title=Beavis and Butt-Head Do America|work=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Geffen Pictures]]<ref name=afi/>\n}}\n| distributor = [[Paramount Pictures]]<ref name=afi/>\n| released = {{Film date|1996|12|20}}\n| runtime = 81 minutes<!-- US theatrical runtime: 80:57 --><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/AFF066576/ |title=Title << British Board of Film Classification |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=January 13, 1997 |accessdate=July 8, 2011}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $12 million<ref name=\"Budget\"/>\n| gross = $63.1 million (US)<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | title=Beavis and Butt-Head Do America (1996 film) | publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=beavisandbuttheaddoamerica.htm | accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America''''' is a 1996 American [[comedy film]]<!-- Please seek consensus at the talk page before changing/adding genres --> based on the [[MTV]] animated television series ''[[Beavis and Butt-Head]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title= Road Trip the Right Vehicle for Beavis and Butt-head|work= The Los Angeles Times|date=December 20, 1996|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1996-12-20/entertainment/ca-10832_1_mike-judge|accessdate=November 8, 2010|first=Kevin|last=Thomas}}</ref> Co-written and directed by series creator [[Mike Judge]], the film  stars the regular television cast of Judge with guest performances by [[Demi Moore]], [[Bruce Willis]], [[Robert Stack]] and [[Cloris Leachman]]. The film centers on [[Beavis]] and [[Butt-Head]] as they travel across the country in an attempt to [[Sexual intercourse|score]].\n\nPrevious offers by MTV to create a film version of ''Beavis and Butt-Head'' were rejected by Judge, but he eventually accepted one in 1994. When the film went into production, Judge and the show's staff halted production on the series while Judge and [[Joe Stillman]] wrote the script. They conceived numerous plot ideas with Judge's being the one developed into a film. [[John Frizzell (composer)|John Frizzell]] composed the film's score.\n\n''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America'' was praised by critics and proved to be a major box office hit from its release on December 20, 1996 by [[Paramount Pictures]], grossing $63.1 million in the United States, becoming the biggest December box office opening in history until it was beaten the following year by ''[[Scream 2]]'' and subsequently one week later by ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''. Although not the only time a feature film was based on an MTV cartoon, it was MTV's only theatrically released animated film.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Beavis]] and [[Butt-Head]] discover that someone has stolen their [[television]], and they set out to find it. After several failed attempts to get a TV, they come across a motel which offers one in every room. They meet Muddy Grimes, who thinks that the boys are the [[Contract killing|hitmen]] he has contacted. Muddy offers Beavis and Butt-Head $10,000 to \"[[Murder|do]]\" his wife, Dallas. Thinking that \"do\" refers to sex, Butt-Head convinces Beavis that both of them can \"score\" and get paid enough to buy a new TV. Muddy hands them a photo of Dallas with instructions on where to find her and drives them to the airport to catch a plane to [[Las Vegas]].\n\nAfter arriving in the casino, Beavis and Butt-Head are ushered to the room Muddy booked, which is located next to Dallas's. They [[Eavesdropping|eavesdrop]] on the opposite room but are caught by Dallas. Dallas offers them $20,000 to go back and \"do\" Muddy, which they refuse. When Beavis (who has removed his pants) and Butt-Head begin arguing over who will \"do\" Dallas first, she realizes that they have misunderstood what they have been hired for. While they are fist fighting, she plants a stolen [[Biological agent|biological weapon]] known as the \"X-5 Unit\" in Beavis's pants in order to get rid of it. She then gets them tickets on a tour bus en route to [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C]]. and instructs them that she will be waiting for them in the [[US Capitol]] and will let them \"do her\" there.\n\nThe stolen bioweapon attracts the attention of the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms|ATF]], headed by Agent Flemming, who orders a [[body cavity search]] on everyone he encounters. Flemming becomes convinced that the duo are [[Criminal mastermind|criminal masterminds]] after they accidentally release the water behind the [[Hoover Dam]], cutting the power to Las Vegas. They are placed on the FBI's most wanted list. After a visit to the [[Grand Canyon]] and [[Yellowstone National Park]],  they fail return to the tour bus on time. Beavis and Butt-Head accidentally ride a busload of [[Nun|nuns]]; repulsed by the boys' actions, the nuns later abandon them at a gift shop in [[Petrified Forest National Park]]. They are then told Washington is about 2,000 miles away and begin to hike until they reach the [[desert]] where they meet two former [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] [[Road crew|roadies]] who are heavily implied to be their fathers, but part ways before they can make the connection.\n\nThe next day the boys begin to hike once more, but they soon collapse from [[dehydration]]. Beavis has a series of hallucinations(animated by [[Rob Zombie]]) after eating a [[Peyote|peyote cacti]] (thinking that there's water inside.) They are eventually found by Muddy, who plans to kill them after realizing they were not the hitmen he hired. However, after hearing that Dallas is going to meet up with the duo in Washington, Muddy decides to take them the rest of the way in his trunk to hunt her down. The boys escape by jumping onto the interstate, inadvertently causing a 400-car [[Multiple-vehicle collision|pileup]]. They casually walk past the scene and get back on the tour bus, stopping at the Capitol before finally reaching the [[White House]]. Before Dallas can meet with Beavis and Butt-Head to recover the bioweapon, she is confronted in the [[Multistorey car park|parking garage]] by Muddy. Dallas, however, seduces him and they briefly reconcile and have sex in his car. The ATF catches them on the act and faced with the possibility of a 60-year jail sentence. Dallas betrays Muddy by saying that he hid the bioweapon in Beavis's pants.\n\nThe ATF is dispatched to the White House due to Beavis and Butt-Head being there on the same day as a peace conference. Beavis consumes [[Caffeine|caffeine pills]], [[sugar]], and [[coffee]] while on the White House tour, transforming him into [[Cornholio]]. Cornholio wanders into the [[Oval Office]] and picks up the [[Moscow\u2013Washington hotline|red phone]], causing the military to go to [[DEFCON 4]]. Meanwhile, Butt-Head tries hitting on [[Chelsea Clinton]], but he gets thrown out of her bedroom window as well as detained and cavity searched by ATF officers. Beavis leaves the White House and goes to Mr. Anderson's [[Caravan (towed trailer)|trailer]], where Anderson catches him after catching him \"[[Masturbation|whacking off]]\" and throws him out. The ATF spots Beavis walking around the camper pants-less and confronts him, thinking he has the bioweapon on him. As the ATF is about to open fire, Anderson opens his camper door and throws out Beavis's pants. The pants are ripped open by the ATF, with the bioweapon flying out of them. The weapon lands safely in Butt-Head's hand, who then hands it to Flemming. Blame for the crime is ultimately pinned on Anderson and his wife, who are accused of trying to frame Beavis and Butt-Head, and arrested along with Dallas and Muddy. Flemming informs the boys that they are heroes and their adventure will remain [[Classified information|top secret]]. They meet President [[Bill Clinton]], who makes them honorary ATF agents. Beavis and Butt-Head return to Highland and find their TV in front of the motel.\n\n==Voice cast==\n{| style=\"float:right\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top\"\n|[[File:Demi Moore 2010 Time 100 Shankbone.jpg|thumb|upright|none|[[Demi Moore]] voices Dallas Grimes]]\n|[[File:Bruce Willis by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|none|[[Bruce Willis]] voices Muddy Grimes]]\n|[[File:Mike Judge by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|none|Mike Judge, voice of Beavis and Butt-head for TV, returned to work on the film]]\n|}\n<!-- main cast only -->\n* [[Mike Judge]] as [[Beavis]], [[Butt-Head]],  [[List of Beavis and Butt-Head characters#Tom Anderson|Tom Anderson (Old Guy with Camper)]],  [[List of Beavis and Butt-Head characters#Mr. Van Driessen|Van Driessen (Hippie Teacher)]], and [[List of Beavis and Butt-Head characters#Highland High faculty and staff|Principal McVicker]]\n* [[Bruce Willis]] as Muddy Grimes\n* [[Demi Moore]] as Dallas Grimes\n* [[Cloris Leachman]] as Old Woman On Plane and Bus\n* [[Robert Stack]] as Agent Flemming\n\n<!-- also starring voice cast in alpha order, closing credits -->\nOther voice actors include: Jacqueline Barba, [[Pamela Blair]], [[Eric Bogosian]], [[Kristofor Brown]], Tony Darling, [[John Doman]], Francis DuMaurier, [[Jim Flaherty]], Tim Guinee, Earl Hofert, [[Toby Huss]], [[Sam Johnson]], [[Richard Linklater]], Rosemary McNamara, Harsh Nayyar, [[Karen Phillips]], Dale Reeves, Mike Ruschak, and Gail Thomas\n\n[[Greg Kinnear]] had an uncredited role as ATF Agent Bork,<ref name=\"cinemablend\">https://www.cinemablend.com/dvds/Beavis-Butthead-Do-America-Special-Collector-Edition-1817.html</ref> [[David Letterman]] had a role as a [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] [[roadie]] and was credited under \"Earl Hofert\".<ref name=\"ifc\">https://www.ifc.com/2016/01/15-things-you-might-not-know-about-beavis-and-butt-head</ref>\n\n==Production==\nDevelopment for the film began in 1993 as part of a production deal with [[MTV]], [[David Geffen]], and [[Warner Bros.]] Geffen so believed in the potential of the ''Beavis and Butt-head'' TV series that he suggested creating a movie and record album based on the program. They originally conceived it as a live action movie, with ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' regulars [[David Spade]] and [[Adam Sandler]] in mind to play the title characters. After MTV's parent company [[Viacom (original)|Viacom]] purchased [[Paramount Pictures]] in 1994, the studio became a partner in the film, replacing Warner's interest in the project and dropping the live action concept under pressure from ''Beavis and Butt-Head'' creator [[Mike Judge]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Geffen Camp Heh-Hehs All the Way to the Bank |date=January 17, 1997 |work=The Los Angeles Times |first=Claudia |last=Ellen |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997-01-17/business/fi-19392_1_david-geffen}}</ref> Judge has stated production of the animated film was very [[ad hoc]] and had some difficulties with progressing due to most of the staff's television background. Beavis' hallucination sequence's design and animation was based on the works of [[Rob Zombie]]. The sequence's director was [[Chris Prynoski]]. <!-- This information is taken from the 2006 DVD release's end credits. -->\n\n===Deleted scene===\nWhen the film premiered on MTV on August 7, 1999, an additional [[deleted scene]] followed the airing: while visiting the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]], Beavis attempts to [[Defecation|use the restroom]], but cannot because of the lack of toilet paper in the stall. Coincidentally, Butt-head is angry because the urinals lack the automatic flushing mechanisms that had amazed him at [[Yellowstone National Park]]. After the rest of their tour group finishes looking at the encased [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]], Beavis sneaks out, breaks the glass with the U.S. flag pole, and steals it to use as \"T.P. for his bunghole.\" While Archive guards rush to see what happened, Beavis cleans up, and exits the stall with a piece of the Declaration, containing [[John Hancock]]'s signature, stuck to his shoe. The scene does not appear on the DVD, although it is mentioned on the disc's commentary track. In the track, Judge noted that the scene did not [[test screening|test]] well.{{Citation needed|date=June 2007}} Another alternate scene was done for when Butt-Head meets [[Chelsea Clinton]] in her bedroom, which showed her packing up to leave the White House. This alternate scene was created in the event [[Bill Clinton]] lost his [[1996 United States presidential election|1996 re-election bid]] to [[Bob Dole]]. However, by the spring of 1996, Judge ultimately decided to keep the original scene because he felt that it was looking as if Clinton was going to win his bid for re-election, and did so that November.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America'' opened in North America on December 20, 1996, and earned $63.1 million at the US box office after opening at #1 with $20.1 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=1996&wknd=51&p=.htm |title=Weekend Box Office Results for December 20-22, 1996 |publisher=Box Office Mojo |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> It had a $12 million production budget.<ref name=\"Budget\">{{cite news|title= Beavis and Butt-head Make Creator and Paramount Proud|work= The Los Angeles Times|date=December 24, 1996|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1996-12-24/entertainment/ca-12081_1_paramount-pictures|accessdate=November 8, 2010 |first=Elaine |last=Dutka}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe film held a 72% approval rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 53 reviews, with a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 6.18/10. The consensus is: \"''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America'' is unabashedly offensive, unapologetically stupid, and unexpectedly funny.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/beavis_and_butt_head_do_america | title=Beavis and Butt-head Do America | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] | accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a 64 out of 100 rating based on 16 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/beavis-and-butt-head-do-america | title=Beavis and Butt-head Do America | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' praised the film as a \"vulgar\" satire on American youth, and compared it favorably  to ''[[Wayne's World (film)|Wayne's World]]''.<ref>[http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/beavis-and-butt-head-do-america-1996 Roger Ebert's review of ''Beavis and Butt-head Do America]</ref> On the movie review show ''[[Siskel and Ebert]]'', Ebert's reviewing partner [[Gene Siskel]] gave the film a \"modest recommendation\", having been taken with the two lead characters. Ebert and Siskel ultimately awarded it a \"[[two thumbs up]]\" rating.<ref>[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=XciJEIa8KIE Siskel and Ebert review ''Beavis and Butt-head Do America'']</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Organization !! Award || Awardee || Result || Citation\n|-\n| [[BMI Awards|BMI Film & TV Awards]] || BMI Film Music Award || [[John Frizzell]] || {{won}} || {{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n|-\n| [[1997 MTV Movie Awards]] || Best On-Screen Duo || rowspan=3 | [[Beavis and Butt-Head]] || {{nom}} || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/archive/year.jhtml?year=1997|title=1997 MTV Movie Awards|work=[[MTV.com]]|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[17th Golden Raspberry Awards]] || Worst New Star || {{nom}} || rowspan=2|<ref>{{cite book|title=The Official Razzie Movie Guide|last=Wilson|first=John|publisher=[[Grand Central Publishing]]|year=2007|isbn=9780446510080|chapter=Seventeenth Annual Razzies (1996)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bLpJHjGFNk8C&pg=PT259}}</ref>\n|-\n| Worst Screen Couple || {{nom}}\n|}\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released on [[VHS]] on June 10, 1997 and on [[DVD]] on November 23, 1999, by [[Paramount Home Entertainment]]. The bonus features on the disc were a [[widescreen]] presentation, and two theatrical trailers. The film was re-released on a Special Edition DVD in 2006 as \"The Edition That Doesn't Suck\". It contained more in the way of bonus features such as [[Audio commentary|audio commentaries]], Spanish language tracks, more trailers, \"Making of\" documentaries, and more. It lacks the deleted National Archives scene. In 2013, \"The Edition That Doesn't Suck\" was re-released on DVD exclusively by Warner Home Video, under a deal with Paramount. Oddly enough, Warner Bros. was Geffen's distributor until The Geffen Company went bankrupt. Today, Warner Bros. holds home video distribution rights to all of Geffen Pictures' library.\n\n==Future==\n===Possible sequel===\nIn the years following, many fans rumored the possibility of a sequel or follow-up to the film, tentatively titled ''Beavis and Butt-Head: The Sequel''<ref name=\"screenrant.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/beavis-and-butt-head-movie-mike-judge-kofi-23670/|title=Beavis and Butt-Head: The Sequel?|last=Outlaw|first=Kofi|date=August 31, 2009|website=[[Screen Rant]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610183835/https://screenrant.com/beavis-and-butt-head-movie-mike-judge/|archive-date=June 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> or ''Beavis and Butt-Head 2''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://cinemablend.com/new/Comic-Con-Mike-Judge-Teases-Beavis-Butt-Head-2-14086.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-09-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004002256/http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Comic-Con-Mike-Judge-Teases-Beavis-Butt-Head-2-14086.html |archive-date=2016-10-04 |url-status=live }}</ref> On August 31, 2009, during the promotion of ''[[Extract (film)|Extract]]'', [[Mike Judge]] said he would like to see Beavis and Butt-Head on the big screen again.<ref name=\"screenrant.com\"/>\n\n===Possible live-action reboot===\nIn 2019 Judge, revealed that he has \"some ideas\" for a new film, saying there might be potential for a live-action version of the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/mike-judge-has-some-ideas-for-new-beavis-and-butt-head-movie|title=Mike Judge has \"some ideas\" for new Beavis and Butt-Head movie|last=Hammer|first=Alice Pattillo2019-07-29T12:08:36Z Metal|website=Metal Hammer Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Beavis and Butt-Head Do America: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = various artists\n| cover      = \n| caption    = \n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 5, 1996\n| recorded   = 1995\u201396\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]<br>[[alternative rock]]<br>[[punk rock]]<br>[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=49|s=00}}\n| label      = [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Mike Judge]] <small>([[Executive producer|exec.]])</small>|[[Butthole Surfers]]|[[Isaac Hayes]]|[[Silkski|Jerome Evans]]|[[John Frizzell (composer)|John Frizzell]]|[[Lars Frederiksen]]|Mark Williams|[[Moby]]|[[No Doubt]]|[[Rashad Smith]]|[[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]|[[Southern Culture on the Skids]]|[[Sylvia Massy]]|[[Terry Date]]|[[Tim Armstrong]]|[[Ulrich Wild]]|[[Vanda & Young]]|[[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie]]}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Beavis and Butt-Head Do America: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n | type        = soundtrack\n | single1     = [[Lesbian Seagull]]\n | single1date = 1996\n | single2     = [[Love Rollercoaster#Red Hot Chili Peppers version|Love Rollercoaster]]\n | single2date = November 1996\n | single3     = [[Ain't Nobody#LL Cool J version|Ain't Nobody]]\n | single3date = November 26, 1996\n | single4     = Walk On Water\n | single4date = 1996\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|2|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r241210|pure_url=yes}} link]\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2Score = C [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,294925_2,00.html link]\n}}\n# \"Two Cool Guys\" \u2013 [[Isaac Hayes]] (3:06)\n# \"[[Love Rollercoaster#Red Hot Chili Peppers cover version|Love Rollercoaster]]\" \u2013 [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] (4:37)\n# \"[[Ain't Nobody#LL Cool J version|Ain't Nobody]]\" \u2013 [[LL Cool J]] (4:38)\n# \"Ratfinks, Suicide Tanks and Cannibal Girls\" \u2013 [[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie]] (3:53)\n# \"I Wanna Riot\" \u2013 [[Rancid (band)|Rancid]] with [[Stubborn All-Stars]] (3:59)\n# \"Walk on Water\" \u2013 [[Ozzy Osbourne]] (4:18) *\n# \"Snakes\" \u2013 [[No Doubt]] (4:34)\n# \"Pimp'n Ain't EZ\" \u2013 Madd Head (4:21)\n# \"The Lord Is a Monkey\" (Rock Version) \u2013 [[Butthole Surfers]] (4:44)\n# \"White Trash\" \u2013 [[Southern Culture on the Skids]] (2:03)\n# \"[[Powerage|Gone Shootin']]\" \u2013 [[AC/DC]] (5:05)\n# \"[[Lesbian Seagull]]\" \u2013 [[Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)|Engelbert Humperdinck]] (3:39)\n\nNoticeably missing are \"Mucha Muchacha\", the version of \"[[Lesbian Seagull]]\" with Mr. Van Driessen singing, and the score tracks performed by The London Metropolitan Orchestra, which were released on a separate album.\n\n\"Two Cool Guys\", written and performed by [[Soul music|soul]]/[[funk]] musician Isaac Hayes, is a semi-parody of Hayes' [[Academy Award]]-winning \"[[Theme from Shaft|Theme from ''Shaft'']]\". It incorporates the theme from the ''Beavis and Butt-head'' television series as a rhythm guitar line, and series creator Mike Judge, who wrote the theme, is given a co-writing credit with Hayes in the soundtrack liner notes. The opening credit sequence which the song features in is a take-off on popular 1970s cop movies and TV shows with Beavis and Butt-Head as hip ace sleuth Lothario detectives.\n\nThe version of Ozzy Osbourne's \"Walk on Water\" is not the same version included in the film. The film used an earlier demo version, while the soundtrack itself contains a later, revised version. The original demo, which appears in the film, can be found on Osbourne's ''Prince of Darkness'' box set.  Ozzy and co-writer [[Jim Vallance]] both prefer the demo version heard in the film.<ref>{{cite web |title=Walk On Water |url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-osbourne-ozzy-walk.html |website=JimVallance.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414024542/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-osbourne-ozzy-walk.html |archive-date=2015-04-14}}</ref> \"Walk on Water\" was released as a single and peaked at number 28 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Billboard'' singles chart history-Ozzy Osbourne |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=ozzy osbourne|chart=all}} |accessdate=February 17, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090220005053/{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=ozzy osbourne|chart=all}}| archivedate= February 20, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0115641|Beavis and Butt-Head Do America}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.beavis-butthead.com:80/|title=Beavis and Butt-Head Do America official site}}\n* {{mojo title|beavisandbuttheaddoamerica|Beavis and Butt-Head Do America}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|beavis_and_butt_head_do_america|Beavis and Butt-Head Do America}}\n* ''[http://www.bcdb.com/bcdb/cartoon.cgi?film=23613&cartoon=Beavis%20and%20Butt-head%20Do%20America Beavis and Butt-head Do America]'' at the [[Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n* [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20199864,00.html ''Beavis and Butt-Head Do America'' Review] on ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n* [http://consequenceofsound.net/2009/07/cinema-