index.html |title=LeBron, Durant named NBA Players of the Week |date=January 3, 2012 |accessdate=April 2, 2012 |work=www.nba.com |publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110164849/http://www.nba.com/2012/news/01/03/players-of-the-week/index.html |archive-date=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> February 13\u201319,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2012/news/02/20/lebron-james-kevin-durant-players-of-week/index.html |title=Heat's James, Thunder's Durant named Players of the Week |date=February 20, 2012 |accessdate=April 2, 2012 |work=www.nba.com |publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC}}</ref> and March 19\u201325.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2012/news/03/26/players-of-the-week-joe-johnson-kevin-durant/index.html |title=Durant, Johnson named Players of the Week |date=March 26, 2012 |accessdate=April 2, 2012 |work=www.nba.com |publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330074603/http://www.nba.com/2012/news/03/26/players-of-the-week-joe-johnson-kevin-durant/index.html |archive-date=March 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Monthly====\n\n* Kevin Durant was named Western Conference [[2011\u201312 NBA season#Players of the month|Player of the Month]] for February<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2012/news/03/02/players-of-the-month-feb/index.html |title=LeBron James, Kevin Durant win Player of the Month honors |work=NBA.com |publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc. |date=March 2, 2012 |accessdate=April 2, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303014534/http://www.nba.com/2012/news/03/02/players-of-the-month-feb/index.html |archive-date=March 3, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and March<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2012/news/04/04/pierce-durant/index.html |title=Pierce, Durant named Eastern, Western players of the month |work=NBA.com |publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc. |date=April 4, 2012 |accessdate=April 4, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407232617/http://www.nba.com/2012/news/04/04/pierce-durant/index.html |archive-date=April 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> 2012.\n* Coach Scott Brooks was named [[2011\u201312 NBA season#Coaches of the month|Coach of the Month]] for games played in December and January.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2012/news/02/01/coaches-of-the-month/index.html |title=Thibodeau, Brooks named Coaches of the Month |work=NBA.com |publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc |date=February 1, 2012 |accessdate=April 2, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209215759/http://www.nba.com/2012/news/02/01/coaches-of-the-month/index.html |archive-date=February 9, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n====All-Star====\n\n* Durant was named as a starter for the Western Conference in the [[2012 NBA All-Star Game]] played in Orlando, earning the game's [[NBA All-Star Game Most Valuable Player Award|MVP Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/feb/27/durant-wins-nba-all-star-game-mvp-west-beats-east/?page=all |title=Durant wins NBA All-Star Game MVP as West beats East |last=Peay |first=Carla |work=Washington Times |date=February 27, 2012 |accessdate=May 11, 2012 |publisher=The Washginton Times, LLC }}</ref>\n* Russell Westbrook was selected as an All-Star team reserve by a vote of the Western Conference coaches.\n* Thunder Coach [[Scott Brooks]] coached the Western Conference team in the All-Star Game due to the fact that the Thunder lead the Western Conference in winning percentage heading into the All-Star break.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2012/news/features/steve_aschburner/02/24/all-star-coaches/index.html |title=All-Star coaches Brooks, Thibodeau come from same NBA tree |date=February 24, 2012 |accessdate=May 11, 2012 |work=www.nba.com |publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228041620/http://www.nba.com/2012/news/features/steve_aschburner/02/24/all-star-coaches/index.html |archive-date=February 28, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Season====\n\n* Durant won the regular season [[List of National Basketball Association season scoring leaders|scoring title]] by averaging 28.0 points per game, making him only the seventh player in NBA history to win three scoring titles in a row.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/story/2012-04-26/No-Kobe-Bryant-means-NBA-scoring-title-to-Kevin-Durant/54560628/1 |title=No Kobe Bryant means NBA scoring title to Kevin Durant |work=USA Today |last=Shuster |first=Rachel |date=April 27, 2012 |accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref>\n* Reserve guard James Harden was a runaway winner of the [[NBA Sixth Man of the Year Award]], garnering 115 of 119 first-place votes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/gameon/post/2012/05/okc-thunder-james-harden-nba-sixth-man-award-winner/1 |title=Thunder's James Harden wins Sixth Man of the Year award |date=May 10, 2012 |accessdate=May 11, 2012 |last= Falgoust |first=J. Michael |work=USA Today}}</ref>\n* Durant was voted to the All-NBA First Team for the third year in a row, whereas Westbrook was voted to the All-NBA Second Team for the second year in a row.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsok.com/article/3678318 |title=OKC Thunder: Kevin Durant, Russell Westbrook earn All-NBA honors |last=Mayberry |first=Darnell |work=The Oklahoman |date=May 24, 2012 |accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref>\n* Forward Serge Ibaka was voted to the All-NBA Defensive First Team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsok.com/okc-thunder-serge-ibaka-named-to-nbas-all-defensive-team/article/3677983 |title=OKC Thunder: Serge Ibaka named to NBA's all-defensive team  |work=The Oklahoman |date=May 23, 2012 |accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Milestones===\n\n==Injuries and surgeries==\n\nBackup point guard [[Eric Maynor]] had a season-ending torn ACL in his right knee in action at Houston on January 7.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsok.com/article/3638808 |title=OKC loses Maynor to first major injury |date=January 9, 2012 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |work=The Oklahoman |last=Mayberry |first=Darnell}}</ref>\n\nStarting shooting guard [[Thabo Sefolosha]] had a chronic sore right foot, forcing him to miss 23 games from January 30 through March 13.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsok.com/article/3645409 |title=Thunder notebook: Thabo Sefolosha sits; Daequan Cook starts |date=February 1, 2012 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |work=The Oklahoman |last=Mayberry |first=Darnell}}</ref>\n\nShooting guard Daequan Cook sustained a mild MCL sprain in his right knee against the Utah Jazz on March 20, sidelining him for an estimated 2\u20133 weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsok.com/article/3659807 |title=\nThunder notebook: Daequan Cook out 2\u20133 weeks with injury |date=March 21, 2012 |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |work=The Oklahoman |last=Rohde |first=John}}</ref>\n\nGuard James Harden was diagnosed with concussive symptoms after being elbowed in the back of the head on April 22 by Lakers forward [[Metta World Peace]].  Harden was cleared to play for the Thunder's regular season finale against the Denver Nuggets after undergoing NBA-mandated post-concussion tests, but instead sat out until the first game of the playoffs.  World Peace received a seven-game suspension for the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2012/news/04/25/harden-cleared.ap/index.html |title=Thunder's Harden cleared but sits against Nuggets |date=April 25, 2012 |accessdate=May 2, 2012 |work=www.nba.com |publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114013016/http://www.nba.com/2012/news/04/25/harden-cleared.ap/index.html |archive-date=November 14, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Transactions==\n\n===Current roster===\n\nOn June 28, 2011, the Thunder exercised its fourth-year options on guard [[James Harden (basketball)|James Harden]], forward [[Serge Ibaka]], guard [[Eric Maynor]] and center [[Byron Mullens]], as well as its third-year option on center [[Cole Aldrich]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsok.com/article/3581072 |title=OKC Thunder exercise contract options on 5 players |date=June 28, 2011 |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |work=The Oklahoman}}</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 2011, the Thunder signed center [[Nazr Mohammed]] to a one-year extension through 2011\u201312, avoiding his becoming an unrestricted free agent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.newsok.com/thunderrumblings/2011/06/29/nazr-mohammed-agrees-to-extension/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110707205308/http://blog.newsok.com/thunderrumblings/2011/06/29/nazr-mohammed-agrees-to-extension/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 7, 2011 |title=Nazr Mohammed Agrees To Extension |last=Mayberry |first=Darnell |work=The Oklahoman |date=June 29, 2011 |accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref> Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but reported to be $3,750,000 for the year.<ref name=HoopsHypeSalaries>{{cite web |url=http://hoopshype.com/salaries/oklahoma_city.htm |work=www.hoopshype.com |title=Oklahoma City Salaries |accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn June 27, 2011, the Thunder provided guard [[Daequan Cook]] a qualifying offer of $3,126,764 for 2011\u201312, making Cook a restricted free agent under the terms of the NBA Collective Bargaining Agreement set to expire after June 30, 2011.<ref name=HoopsHypeSalaries/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsok.com/article/3580833 |title=Thunder makes Daequan Cook a restricted free agent |date=June 27, 2011 |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |work=The Oklahoman |last=Mayberry |first=Darnell}}</ref> Cook's contract situation was resolved after the NBA lockout when the Thunder signed him to a contract extension paying him $6.5 million through the end of the 2012\u201313 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsok.com/article/3630988 |title=Thunder notebook: Guard Daequan Cook agrees to two-year extension |date=December 9, 2011 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |work=The Oklahoman |last=Mayberry |first=Darnell}}</ref>\n\nOn December 13, 2011, the Thunder traded [[Robert Vaden (basketball)|Robert Vaden]] and two conditional second-round draft selections to the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]] in exchange for [[Lazar Hayward]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/timberwolves/news/hayward_trade_okc_2011_12_13.html |title=Timberwolves Trade Lazar Hayward to Oklahoma City |date=December 13, 2011 |accessdate=June 28, 2012 |work=NBA Media Ventures, LLC}}</ref>\n\n===Free agents===\n\nOn March 21, 2012, the Thunder signed point guard [[Derek Fisher]] for the remainder of the 2012 season, after waiving its second-round 2010 draft pick forward [[Ryan Reid]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsok.com/article/feed/362547 |title=Derek Fisher signs with Oklahoma City Thunder |date=March 21, 2012 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |work=The Oklahoman |last=Latzke |first=Jeff}}</ref>  Fisher had previously been traded form the Los Angeles Lakers to the Houston Rockets on March 15, but the Rockets subsequently bought out Fisher's contract making him an unrestricted free agent.\n\n===Transaction summary table===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable sortable\"\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}}\" width=\"15%\"| Date\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}}\" width=\"15%\"| Transaction Type\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}}\" width=\"30%\"| Thunder Acquired\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}}\" width=\"30%\"| Thunder Subtracted\n|- style=\"text-align: left\"\n| December 11, 2011\n| Draftee signing\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Reggie Jackson (basketball, born 1990)|Reggie Jackson]]\n|\n|- style=\"text-align: left\"\n| December 12, 2011\n| Draftee signing\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Ryan Reid]]\n|\n|- style=\"text-align: left\"\n| December 13, 2011\n| Roster trade\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Lazar Hayward]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Robert Vaden (basketball)|Robert Vaden]] (to Minnesota)<br>'''\u2022''' two conditional second-round picks (to M